1 Nov 2016: Liberia moves to revive economy after Ebola
http://www.iol.co.za/business/news/liberia-moves-to-revive-economy-after-ebola-2085617
[According to Finance and Development Planning Minister Boima Kamara, Liberia will need USD 1.3 billion to revive an economy that was ravaged by a slump in its key export commodities and the worst epidemic of [Ebola virus disease (EVD)]. Kamara also said Liberia will invest in energy projects to stimulate its manufacturing sector while prioritizing agriculture after economic expansion almost came to a standstill over the past 3 years, Kamara said in an interview in the capital, Monrovia. The country is targeting average annual economic growth of about 6 percent for the 7 years starting 2018, after averaging about 8 percent between 2006 and 2013.]

4 Nov 2016 Liberia: International Monetary Fund says Liberia's economy "still not recovering"
http://www.frontpageafricaonline.com/index.php/business/2459-international-monetary-fund-says-liberia-s-economy-still-not-recovering
[The International Monetary Fund (IMF) says that despite its projection that Liberia's GDP growth is poised to recover to about 3 percent in 2017, the post-war, [Ebola virus disease (EVD)]-hit nation is yet to recover from effects of the EVD outbreak that killed a total of 4810 Liberian residents.
According to an End-of-Mission news release by the monetary body's team following a recent visit to Monrovia [Liberia], performance on the economic program supported by an Extended Credit Facility (ECF) has been uneven.]

1 Nov 2016 USA: Revealed--Record numbers of Americans traveled abroad last year (2015) despite concerns over Zika, Ebola and terrorism
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/travel_news/article-3893042/Record-numbers-Americans-travelled-abroad-year-despite-concerns-Zika-Ebola-terrorism.html#ixzz4OmqaXA5L

[According to the Department of Commerce, 74 million US residents traveled internationally in 2015. This figure rose year-on-year for the past 4 years, including 9 percent last year [2015]. Of those, 33 million traveled overseas, with United Kingdom the most popular destination.]
[It is encouraging that people continue to travel in spite of media reports on danger from health related issues and terrorism, as it broadens the mind and increases cross-cultural understanding. However, most of the travel was to Mexico, Canada, and the UK, so Americans may not be as adventurous as it 1st appears. - Mod.LK]

